 <i>here</i> ‘army’) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’."]},{"name":"Earls","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with genitival <i>-s</i>, denoting someone who was a member of an earl's household, or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In Ireland, when this is not the English name, it is from Gaelic <b>Mac an Iarla</b> ‘son of the earl’."]},{"name":"Hearl","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Count","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Earll","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Earl  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Earl was born about 1470, in London, Middlesex, England, her father, Sir Robert Rix, Earl of Offord, was 21 and her mother, Ann Periam, was 21. She had at least 1 son with John William Periam. She died about 1530, at the age of 62."},"et":{"about 1470–about 1530":"umbes 1470–umbes 1530","1470–1530":"1470–1530","1480–1536":"1480–1536","1482–Male":"1482–Surnud","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1488–1549":"1488–1549","1450–1536":"1450–1536","1450–1486":"1450–1486","1536":"1536","about 1470":"umbes 1470","1488":"1488","1486":"1486","1530":"1530","25 June 1486":"25. juuni 1486","1450":"1450","about 1530":"umbes 1530","1482":"1482","1